<section xml:id="sec-simple-modules" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simple modules</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We define simple modules and study some of their properties. We begin with the definition of <sq>cyclic modules</sq>. Throughout this section, we assume that <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with unity and <m>A</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra. All modules are right <m>A</m>-modules.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-cyclic-module">
        <title>Cyclic module</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra and <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module. We say that <m>M</m> is a <em>cyclic module</em> if there exists <m>m\in M</m> such that <m>M=mA</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-cyclic-module-and-annihilator">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra and <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module which is cyclic. Then,
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>M\simeq A/\Ann{A}{M}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>N</m> is a right ideal of <m>A</m> then, <m>A/N</m> is a cyclic right <m>A</m>-module.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>N</m> be a right ideal of <m>A</m>. Put <m>B=\{a\in A:aN\subseteq N\}</m>. Then, <m>B</m> is a subalgebra of <m>A</m> containing <m>N</m>. Furthermore, <m>\End{A}{A/N}\simeq B/N</m> as right <m>B</m>-modules.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Suppose that <m>M=mA</m>. Define a map <m>\varphi\colon A\to M</m> by <m>a\mapsto m\cdot a</m>. As <m>M</m> is cyclic, the map is surjective and its kernel is precisely <m>\Ann{A}{M}</m>. The first isomorphism theorem for modules gives the required isomorphism.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Checking <m>A/N</m> is a right <m>A</m>-module is left to the reader. Consider the submodule of <m>N</m> generated by <m>1+N</m>. Given any <m>a+N\in A/N</m> we have <m>a+N=(1+N)\cdot a</m>, and therefore, <m>A/N\simeq (1+N)(A/N)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We first check that <m>B</m> is a subalgebra of <m>A</m> containing <m>N</m>. For <m>b\in B\subseteq A</m>, <m>n\in N</m>, and <m>r\in R</m> we have
                        <me>
                            (b\cdot r)n =b(n\cdot r), \text{as }n\in N\subseteq A\text{ and using algebra condition }<xref ref="eqn-algebra"/>.
                        </me>
                        As <m>N</m> is a right ideal of <m>A</m> and hence <m>n\cdot r\in N</m>. This shows that <m>b\cdot r\in B</m>. We leave to the reader to check other conditions for <m>B</m> to be a subalgebra of <m>A</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Note that <m>A/N</m> is a right <m>A</m>-module and so is <m>\End{A}{A/N}</m>. As <m>B\hookrightarrow A</m> is a subalgebra, <m>\End{A}{A/N}</m> is also a right <m>B</m>-module. We define <m>\varphi\colon\End{A}{A/N}\to B/N</m> by <m>f\mapsto f(1)+N</m>. We check that <m>\varphi</m> is a <m>B</m>-module homomorphism. For <m>f,g\in\End{A}{A/N}</m>, and <m>b,b'\in B</m> we have
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \varphi(f\cdot b+g\cdot b')\amp =(f\cdot b)(1)+(g\cdot b')(1)+N</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =(f(1)\cdot b)+N+(g(1)\cdot b')+N</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =\varphi(f)\cdot b+\varphi(g)\cdot b'.</mrow>
                        </md>
                        For <m>b+N\in B/N</m> consider <m>\ell_b\colon A/N\to A/N</m> given by <m>\ell_b(a+N)=ba+N</m>, i.e., coset representative <m>a</m> maps to a coset representative <m>ba</m>. We check the well-definedness of this map. Suppose that <m>a\equiv a'\mod N</m>, say <m>a'=a+n</m> for some <m>n\in N</m>. We obtain the following:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\ell_b(a'+N) \amp=\ell_b((a+n)+N) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=\left(b(a+n)\right)+N </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=(ba+bn)+N </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=ba+N\text{ (by the definition of }B,\, bn\in N) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=\ell_b(a+N) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Suppose now that <m>b'=b+n</m> for some <m>n\in N</m>. We check that <m>\ell_b=\ell_{b'}</m>.
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\ell_{b'}(a+N) \amp=\ell_{b+n}(a+N) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=((b+n)a)+N </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=(ba+na)+N </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=ba+N\text{ (as }na\in N\text{, since }N\text{ is a right ideal of }A) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp=\ell_b(a+N) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Furthermore, the map <m>\ell_b</m> is <m>A</m>-linear. Indeed, for <m>a,a'\in A</m> we have <me>\ell_b\left((a+N)\cdot a'\right)=\ell_b(aa'+N)=(baa')+N=\ell_b(a+N)\cdot a'.</me>
                        Therefore, we ge the map <m>\psi\colon B/N\to\End{A}{A/N}</m> given by <m>b+N\mapsto\ell_b</m>. One may check that <m>\varphi</m> and <m>\psi</m> are mutually inverse homomorphisms of <m>B</m>-modules.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Every cyclic group is a cyclic <m>\Z</m>-module.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Suppose that <m>T\colon\R^2\to\R^2</m> be an <m>\R</m>-linear map defined by <m>Te_1=e_1</m> and <m>Te_2=e_1+e_2</m>. We consider <m>\R^2</m> as a module over <m>\R[x]</m> via <m>T</m>. Note that <m>T-\unit\neq 0</m> but <m>(T-\unit)^2=0</m>. In fact <m>(T-\unit)e_2=e_1</m> and hence, <m>\{e_2,(T-\unit)e_2\}</m> is a basis of <m>\R^2</m>. This shows that <m>\R^2</m> is a cyclic <m>\R[x]</m>-module generated by <m>e_2</m>. By <xref ref="lem-cyclic-module-and-annihilator"/>, we have <m>\R^2\simeq \R[x]/(x-1)^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra. Consider <m>A</m> as a right <m>A</m>-module over itself. Then, the cyclic submodules of <m>A</m> are precisely the right principal ideal of <m>A</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-simple-module">
        <title>Simple module</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with unity, and <m>A</m> be an <m>R</m>-algebra. A right <m>A</m>-module <m>N</m> is said to be <em>simple</em> if <m>N</m> is nonzero and only submodules of <m>N</m> are <m>0</m> and <m>N</m> itself.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="ex-minimal-right-ideal-of-matrix-algebra">
        <title>Minimal right ideal of matrix algebra</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>D</m> is a division algebra over a field <m>F</m>, and that <m>M_n(D)</m> is <m>n\times n</m> matrix algebra over <m>D</m>. Consider the following set.
                <me>
                    M_1=\left\{\begin{pmatrix}d_{11}\amp d_{12}\amp\cdots\amp d_{1n}\\0\amp 0\amp\cdots\amp 0\\\vdots\amp\vdots\amp\ddots\amp\vdots\\0\amp 0\amp\cdots\amp 0\end{pmatrix}:d_{1i}\in D\right\}
                </me>
                The <m>M_1</m> is a right ideal of <m>M_n(D)</m>. We consider <m>M_1</m> as a right <m>M_n(D)</m>-module. We claim that <m>M_1</m> is a simple right <m>M_n(D)</m>-module. Suppose that <m>0\neq A=(a_{ij})\in M_1</m>, say <m>a_{1k}\neq 0</m>. As <m>D</m> is a division algebra, there exists <m>b_k\in D</m> such that <m>1=b_ka_{1k}=a_{1k}b_k</m>. Assume that <m>E_{\ell k}</m> to be the matrix with <m>(\ell,k)</m>-th entry <m>1</m> and all other entries <m>0</m>. One check that <m>A\cdot E_{k k}b_k=E_{1k}\in AM_n(D)</m>. This shows that for <m>d_{11},d_{12},\ldots,d_{1n}\in D</m>,
                <me>
                    \sum_{k=1}^n E_{1k}d_{1k}=\begin{pmatrix}d_{11}\amp d_{12}\amp\cdots\amp d_{1n}\\0\amp 0\amp\cdots\amp 0\\\vdots\amp\vdots\amp\ddots\amp\vdots\\0\amp 0\amp\cdots\amp 0\end{pmatrix}\in AM_n(D).
                </me>
                Therefore, <m>AM_n(D)=M_1</m>, i.e., <m>M_1</m> is a simple right <m>M_n(D)</m>-module.
            </p>
            <p>
                The above arguments show that <m>M</m> is a minimal right ideal of <m>M_n(D)</m>, and that for any <m>0\neq A\in M_1</m> we have <m>M_n(D)</m>-module isomorphism <m>AM_n(D)\simeq M_1</m>. Furthermore, if we denote by <m>M_i</m> as the set of matrices in <m>M_n(D)</m> whose only nonzero row can be the <m>i</m>-th row, then each <m>M_i</m> is a minimal right ideal of <m>M_n(D)</m>. Note that <m>M_n(D)=\bigoplus_{i=1}^n M_i</m>. One may also check that <m>M_i\simeq M_j</m> for every <m>i,j</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-equivalent-criterion-for-simple-modules">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M</m> be a nonzero right <m>A</m>-module. Following conditions are equivalent.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>M</m> is simple;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For any nonzero <m>m\in M</m>, <m>M\simeq mA</m>;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>M\simeq A_A/\mathfrak{m}</m> for some maximal right ideal <m>\mathfrak{m}</m> of <m>A</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Assume that <m>M</m> is simple and that <m>m\in M</m> is nonzero. Thus, the submodule generated by <m>m</m>, <m>mA</m> is a nonzero submodule of <m>M</m>. Thus, <m>M=mA</m>. Conversely, if <m>M=mA</m> for any nonzero element <m>m\in M</m> then, for any nonzero submodule <m>N\leq M</m> and <m>0\neq n\in N</m>, we have <m>M=nA\leq N\leq M</m>, i.e., <m>N=M</m>, i.e., <m>M</m> is simple.
        </p>
        <p>
            We fix a nonzero element <m>m\in M</m> and define a map <m>f\colon A\to mA</m> by <m>a\mapsto m\cdot a</m>. This is a surjective <m>A</m>-module homomorphism. The kernel of <m>f</m> is
            <me>
                \ker f=\{a\in A:m\cdot a=0\}=\Ann{A}{m}.
            </me>
            By <xref ref="lem-annihilator-of-module-is-ideal"/>, <m>\ker f</m> is a right ideal of <m>A</m>. By the isomorphism theorem, <m>A_A/\ker f\simeq mA</m>. By the Correspondence theorem, submodules of <m>mA</m> corresponds to right ideals of <m>A</m> containing <m>\ker f</m>. Thus, <m>M</m> is simple if and only if there are no proper right ideals of <m>A</m> containing <m>\ker f</m>. This proves the equivalence of (1) and (3).
        </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
        Using the above <xref ref="prop-equivalent-criterion-for-simple-modules"/> we obtain the following important lemma. Its proof is left to the reader.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-schur-lemma">
        <title>Schur's lemma</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> be right <m>A</m>-modules, and <m>f\colon M\to N</m> be a nonzero <m>A</m>-module homomorphism.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>M</m> is simple then, <m>f</m> is injective.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>N</m> is simple then, <m>f</m> is surjective.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-schur-lemma">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>M</m> and <m>N</m> are simple <m>A</m>-modules then either <m>M\simeq N</m> or <m>\Hom{A}{M}{N}=0</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <definition xml:id="def-semisimple-module">
        <title>Semisimple module</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                A right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> is said to be <em>semisimple</em> if <m>M</m> is a direct sum of simple <m>A</m>-modules.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="ex-matrix-algebra-is-semisimple">
        <title>Matrix algebra is semisimple</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                We have shown in <xref ref="ex-minimal-right-ideal-of-matrix-algebra"/> that <m>M_n(D)</m> is a semisimple <m>M_n(D)</m>-module.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-indecomposable-module">
        <title>Indecomposable module</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                A right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> is said to be <em>indecomposable</em> if <m>M\neq 0</m> and that if <m>M=P\oplus Q</m> for some submodules <m>P,Q</m> then, either <m>P=0</m> or <m>Q=0</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="ex-indecomposable-need-not-imply-simple">
        <title>Indecomposable module need not be simple</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Every simple <m>A</m>-module is indecomposable. However, the converse need not be true, as shown below.
            </p>
            <p>
                Consider <m>\Z/4\Z</m> as a <m>\Z</m>-module. As the subgroup generated by <m>2</m> is a proper nontrivial submodule of <m>M</m>, we conclude that <m>\Z/4\Z</m> is not simple. Recall that there are, up to isomorphism, only two groups of order <m>4</m>, viz., <m>\Z/4\Z</m> and <m>\Z/2\Z\times\Z/2\Z</m>. This shows that <m>\Z/4\Z</m> is indecomposable.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-schur-lemma-indecomposable">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>N</m> be a semisimple right <m>A</m>-module. The following conditions are equivalent.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>N</m> is simple;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\End{A}{N}</m> is division algebra;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>N</m> is indecomposable.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Let <m>N</m> is simple. By <xref ref="lem-schur-lemma"/>, every nonzero <m>A</m>-module endomorphism is invertible, i.e., <m>\End{A}{N}</m> is division.
        </p>
        <p>
            Assume that <m>\End{A}{N}</m> is division algebra, and that <m>N+P\oplus Q</m> for some <m>A</m>-submodules <m>P,Q</m> of <m>N</m>. The propjection <m>\pi\colon N\to P</m> (resp., \unit_N-\pi\colon N\to Q) is an <m>A</m>-module homomorphism.
        </p>
    </proof>
</section>